What is the output?
```cpp
int* getBadPointer() {
    int x = 42;
    return &x;
}
int main() {
    int* p = getBadPointer();
    std::cout << *p;
}
```

questions.explanation:
Local variables live on the **stack** and are destroyed when the function returns. Here, `x` is a local `int` inside `getBadPointer()` ŌĆö the function returns `&x` (the address of `x`), but by the time `main()` uses that pointer, `x` no longer exists. The pointer is **dangling**, and dereferencing it is **undefined behavior**.

```cpp
// WRONG: returning address of local variable
int* getBadPointer() { int x = 42; return &x; }

// FIX 1: allocate on the heap (caller must delete)
int* getGoodPointer() { return new int(42); }

// FIX 2: just return by value (preferred)
int getValue() { return 42; }
```

The compiler will usually warn about this ŌĆö always pay attention to "returning address of local variable" warnings.

questions.text:
What is the output?
```cpp
int* p;
{
    int x = 100;
    p = &x;
}
std::cout << *p;
```

questions.explanation:
The variable `x` is local to the inner block `{}` ŌĆö it is created when the block is entered and **destroyed** when the block exits. After the closing `}`, `p` still holds the address where `x` used to be, making it a **dangling pointer**. Dereferencing `*p` is undefined behavior.

This is the same principle as returning a pointer to a local variable from a function ŌĆö once the scope ends, stack memory is reclaimed.

```cpp
// Safe alternative: use dynamic allocation
int* p;
{
    int* temp = new int(100);
    p = temp;  // heap memory survives the block
}
std::cout << *p;  // OK: prints 100
delete p;          // don't forget to free it
```

