What is the output?
```cpp
namespace Physics { double g = 9.81; }
namespace Math { double pi = 3.14; }
int main() {
    std::cout << Physics::g - Math::pi;
}
```

questions.explanation:
Namespaces are an organizational tool ŌĆö they group related names to avoid collisions, but they don't change how values work. Using the scope resolution operator `::`, you can access any member: `Physics::g` is `9.81` and `Math::pi` is `3.14`.

The expression `Physics::g - Math::pi` = `9.81 - 3.14` = `6.67`.

```cpp
// Namespaces prevent name collisions:
namespace Audio { int rate = 44100; }
namespace Video { int rate = 60; }
// Audio::rate and Video::rate are distinct variables
```

Namespaces are essential in large projects ŌĆö they prevent naming conflicts between libraries (e.g., `std::` is the namespace for the entire C++ standard library).

