What is wrong with this code?
```cpp
void foo() {
    int* p = new int(1);
    int* q = new int(2);
    q = p;
    delete q;
}
```

What is the output?
```cpp
int x = 0;
int* p = &x;
*p = 99;
std::cout << x << " " << *p;
```

What is the output?
```cpp
void setToTen(int* p) { *p = 10; }
int main() {
    int x = 0;
    setToTen(&x);
    std::cout << x;
}
```

questions.explanation:
This demonstrates **pass-by-pointer**, which allows a function to modify the caller's variable. `setToTen` receives a pointer `p` that holds the address of `x`. Writing `*p = 10` dereferences the pointer and modifies the value at that address ŌĆö which is `x` in `main()`.

```cpp
void setToTen(int* p) { *p = 10; }  // modifies value at address p
int main() {
    int x = 0;
    setToTen(&x);  // pass address of x
    // x is now 10
}
```

This achieves the same effect as pass-by-reference (`int& p`), but with explicit pointer syntax. The `&x` in the call takes the address of `x`, and `*p` in the function dereferences it. Output: `10`.

