What is wrong with this code?
```cpp
void foo() {
    int* a = new int(1);
    int* b = new int(2);
    delete a;
}
```

questions.explanation:
Every `new` must be paired with a `delete`, or the memory is **leaked**. Here, `a` is properly deleted (freeing the integer `1`), but `b` is never deleted. When the function returns, the local pointer `b` is destroyed ŌĆö but the **heap memory** it pointed to (holding `2`) is not freed. That memory is now unreachable and leaked.

```cpp
void foo() {
    int* a = new int(1);
    int* b = new int(2);
    delete a;  // Ō£ō memory for 1 is freed
    delete b;  // ŌåÉ this line is missing! memory for 2 is leaked
}
```

In modern C++, use **smart pointers** (`std::unique_ptr`) to avoid manual memory management ŌĆö they automatically `delete` when they go out of scope.

questions.text:
What is the output?
```cpp
int* p = new int(5);
int* q = p;
delete p;
std::cout << *q;
```

questions.explanation:
Both `p` and `q` point to the same heap-allocated `int` (because `q = p` copies the address). After `delete p`, that memory is freed ŌĆö but `q` still holds the old address. This makes `q` a **dangling pointer**. Dereferencing it with `*q` is **undefined behavior** ŌĆö it might print `5`, crash, or do anything else.

Safe pattern ŌĆö set pointers to `nullptr` after deleting:
```cpp
delete p;
p = nullptr;
q = nullptr;  // q also pointed to the same memory
// now we can check: if (q != nullptr) before using
```

Even better: use `std::unique_ptr`, which prevents two pointers from owning the same memory and automatically frees it.
